tr.td: I will check postoperative imaging. She will return to see me in one year with repeat imaging. She will call in the interim with any questions or concerns. All discharge instructions were given, and all questions were answered.
Ms. Green is a 67-year-old female who recently underwent removal of a WHO Grade I frontal meningioma on 2019-01-05. She is doing well.

I have discussed with her the diagnosis and the natural history of lesions such as this. She understands that approximately 60% of meningiomas do not grow over a five year period. Her options include observation, surgery, or radiosurgery. The risks and benefits of each option were explained to the patient in detail, and she wishes to proceed with surgery. I think this is reasonable. The planned operation is a right frontal craniotomy for removal of tumor. The risks include but are not limited to bleeding, infection, cerebrospinal fluid leak, stroke, and even death. We will proceed with scheduling. She will call in the interim with any questions or concerns. All discharge instructions were given, and all questions were answered.
Ms. Green is a 67-year-old female who presents for evaluation of a brain tumor. I think it is a symptomatic meningioma involving the right frontal convexity.
